rical work. He also traces the theme of dissent that ran through Butterfield's life and work, presenting a man who found himself at odds with prevailing convictions about history, morality, politics, religion, and teaching, a man who elevated the notion of dissent into an ethic of living in tension with any established system.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Apr 2020) 0aHistorianszGreat BritainvBiography. 0aHistoryxPhilosophy. 0aInternational relationsxPhilosophy. 7aRELIGION / General.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertYUP eBook-Package 2000-2015z978311066772108iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertYale University Press eBook Package 2000-2013z978311053799440uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780300130089423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780300130089.jpg  a978-3-11-053799-4  Yale University Press eBook Package 2000-2013c2000d2013  a978-3-11-066772-1  YUP eBook-Package 2000-2015c2000d2015  aEBA_FAO  aGBV-deGruyter-alles